        SDL_Quit();
    }

    // Public interface for various subsystems (window, renderer, input, audio, etc.)
    Window& GetWindow() { /* return reference to window object */ }
    Renderer& GetRenderer() { /* return reference to renderer object */ }
    // ...other subsystem getter methods...

    void InitializeSubsystems() {
        // Create and initialize engine subsystems like window, renderer, etc.
    }

    void ShutdownSubsystems() {
        // Clean up subsystems
    }

    // ... other engine management methods ...

private:
    // Private members for subsystems like window, renderer, etc.
};
```

And in the game code, you can create an instance of `Engine`, initialize it, and start the main loop:

```cpp
class Game {
public:
    Game(Engine& engine) : engine(engine) {
        // Initialize game state, load assets, etc.
    }

    void Run() {
        // Main game loop
        while (!shouldQuit) {
            // Handle input
            // Update game logic
            // Render
        }
    }

private:
    Engine& engine;
    bool shouldQuit = false;
};
```

Finally, in your `main` function, you would set up the engine and then create and run your game instance:

```cpp
int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    try {
        Engine engine;
        engine.InitializeSubsystems();

        Game game(engine);
        game.Run(); // Game now controls its own main loop

        engine.ShutdownSubsystems();
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Unhandled Exception: " << e.what() << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

This separation allows the `Engine` to manage the fundamental SDL operations and subsystem management, while the `Game` class manages the game-specific logic and loop. This design aligns well with the idea of an engine as a toolbox and a game as the creation built using those tools. Each subsystem of the engine can be accessed and used independently within the `Game`'s main loop, and the `Engine` itself does not dictate the flow of the game logic.

If each of your subsystems like `ScreenManager`, `AudioManager`, `InputManager`, etc. are implemented as singletons with their own initialization and cleanup logic, then your `Engine` class might not need to manage the lifecycle of these individual subsystems explicitly. Instead, the `Engine` could focus on general startup and shutdown procedures, possibly including global states or configurations that apply to the entire engine.

Here's how the `Engine` class might look with singleton subsystems:

```cpp
class Engine {
public:
    Engine() {
        if (SDL_Init(SDL_INIT_EVERYTHING) < 0) { // Initialize all SDL subsystems
            throw std::runtime_error("SDL could not initialize! SDL Error: " + std::string(SDL_GetError()));
        }
        // Additional global initialization can be done here if needed.
    }

    ~Engine() {
        // Any global cleanup can be done here.
        SDL_Quit();
    }

    // The Engine class no longer needs methods to access the subsystems since they are singletons.
    // If global configurations or states are needed, methods to set or retrieve them would be added here.
};
```

Since each subsystem manager is a singleton, they would each have a static method to access their instance:

```cpp
class ScreenManager {
public:
    static ScreenManager& Instance() {
        static ScreenManager instance;
        return instance;
    }

    // ScreenManager methods ...

private:
    ScreenManager() {
        // Initialize ScreenManager specifics...
    }

    ~ScreenManager() {
        // Cleanup...
    }

    // Singleton protections...
    ScreenManager(ScreenManager const&) = delete;
    void operator=(ScreenManager const&) = delete;
};

// AudioManager, InputManager, etc., would have a similar structure.
```

And the `main` function can directly call into these singleton instances as needed:

```cpp
int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    try {
        Engine engine; // Initialize SDL and any other global states

        // Now singletons can be accessed and used without explicitly passing around an Engine instance.
        auto& screenManager = ScreenManager::Instance();
        auto& audioManager = AudioManager::Instance();
        // Other subsystem instances...

        // Game loop or other initialization...
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        std::cerr << "Unhandled Exception: " << e.what() << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

In this setup, each manager is responsible for its own setup and teardown, and this is hidden behind the singleton interface. When an application or game wants to interact with a subsystem, it simply requests the instance of the singleton.

Keep in mind that while singletons provide convenient global access and ensure a single instance, they can have drawbacks like making testing more challenging, possibly creating hidden dependencies, and making it harder to control the initialization order (which can be problematic when one singleton depends on another).

Singletons can work well for global-access objects where there is a clear case that only one instance should exist, but consider carefully whether their use aligns with your engine's architecture and future scalability needs.
